  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Mine Risk Education, Victim Assistance, First Aid, and Psychosocial Support Capacity-Building in Northern Shan State</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="2">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">The proposed project is a humanitarian intervention to mitigate the dangers posed by landmines and explosive remnants of war (ERW) faced by conflict-affected communities in Northern Shan State (NSS). It builds upon MHF-funded interventions implemented by DanChurchAid (DCA), The HALO Trust, and partners between 2015 and July 2017, during which Mine Risk Education (MRE) was delivered to 95,000 individuals. However there continue to be frequent armed clashes in NSS, resulting in significant displacements and mine/ERW contamination in previously unaffected areas. According to data collected by UNICEF, mine/ERW accidents across Myanmar have resulted in more than 90 casualties in the first half of 2017 56 % of these were in NSS.  There is an urgent need for the delivery of additional MRE and the provision of Victim Assistance (VA) and Psychosocial Support (PSS) to survivors to conflict-affected communities.

This project, developed by DCA and HALO with partner organizations Ta&#x2019;ang Students and Youth Union (TSYU), Shan State Youth Network Committee (SSYNC) and Never End Tomorrow (NET, previously Kachin Youth Organization), will be implemented in 11 townships including the four prioritized by the MHF. The project&#x2019;s objectives will be two-fold: 1) Women, girls, boys and men are better aware of the dangers of mines/ERW and adopt safer behavior, and 2) At-risk communities are better equipped to deal with an accident.

 This will be achieved through the following: 
	continuing to use a Training of Trainers (ToT) approach to build partners&#x2019; capacity to deliver MRE, including through MRE tailoring to address the different vulnerabilities of women, girls, men and boys
	delivering MRE, including emergency MRE, to conflict-affected communities
	First Aid training and provision of supplies to Community Implementers
	contingency-based casualty evacuation and emergency cash grants
	supporting partners to mainstream PSS into MRE delivery and
	data collection through victim interviews.</narrative>
  </description>
